{"sections":[{"chapter":"Display your first snippet","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Learn different ways of creating and managing TWSManager"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"kind":"hero","estimatedTimeInMinutes":5,"title":"Creating and managing TWSManager"},{"tasks":[{"contentSection":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In this section you will learn different approaches for creation, registration with remote services and persistance of the TWSManager."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"kind":"contentAndMedia","mediaPosition":"trailing"}],"stepsSection":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"First way to create a TWSManager is by using TWSFactory.new(with:).","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"You provide the factory with your project id and the factory creates or retrieves(if instance for the configuration is already alive) a TWSManager instance for the provided configuration."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"type":"step","media":null,"runtimePreview":null,"caption":[{"name":"Note","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If the instance was created for the first time, you have to register it with remote services to use it. Call registerManager() on the manager instance."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"style":"note","type":"aside"}],"code":"ManagerCreation_00.swift"},{"caption":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Use @Environment(TWSManager.self) to retrieve manager in ancestor views."}]},{"type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This way the manager will persist automatically as long as that view hierarchy is alive."}]}],"style":"note","name":"Note"}],"code":"ManagerCreation_01.swift","media":null,"type":"step","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Another way to create a manager is by using View extension function twsRegister(configuration:), which creates a TWSManager instance with the provided configuration, injects it into the view hiearchy and registers it with remote services.","type":"text"}]}],"runtimePreview":null},{"caption":[],"code":"ManagerCreation_02.swift","media":null,"type":"step","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Last way to do it is using combination of both. You can create an instance using TWSFactory.new(with:) and then register and inject it into the environment using View extension function twsRegister(using:)"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"runtimePreview":null}],"title":"Manager creation and registration","anchor":"Manager-creation-and-registration"}],"kind":"tasks"},{"kind":"callToAction","action":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/MixAndMatch","overridingTitle":"Get started","type":"reference","overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Get started"}],"isActive":true},"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Once you start mixing remote and local snippets, there are a few important considerations to keep in mind. Since the manager is injected into the environment, it can be accessed from anywhere in the app. However, this setup assumes that snippets are handled remotely. To successfully work with both remote and local snippets, you’ll need to follow specific rules and best practices."}],"title":"Combine remote and local snippets","featuredEyebrow":"Tutorial"}],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/tutorials\/tws\/managercreation"]}],"kind":"project","identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/ManagerCreation","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"hierarchy":{"modules":[{"projects":[{"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/LocalSnippet","sections":[{"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/LocalSnippet#Displaying-a-Snippet","kind":"task"}]},{"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/RemoteSnippet","sections":[{"kind":"task","reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/RemoteSnippet#Connect-with-the-TWS-portal"},{"kind":"task","reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/RemoteSnippet#Presenting-snippets"}]},{"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/ManagerCreation","sections":[{"kind":"task","reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/ManagerCreation#Manager-creation-and-registration"}]},{"sections":[{"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/MixAndMatch#Mix-Match","kind":"task"}],"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/MixAndMatch"},{"sections":[{"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/Notifications#Integrating-TWSNotifications","kind":"task"}],"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/Notifications"}],"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/Tutorial-Table-of-Contents\/Display-your-first-snippet"},{"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/Tutorial-Table-of-Contents\/Customizing-TWSView","projects":[{"sections":[{"kind":"task","reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/CustomizingViews#Custom-loading-and-error-views"}],"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/CustomizingViews"},{"sections":[{"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/CustomInterceptor#Custom-interceptors","kind":"task"}],"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/TWS\/CustomInterceptor"}]}],"paths":[["doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/Tutorial-Table-of-Contents","doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/Tutorial-Table-of-Contents\/$volume","doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/Tutorial-Table-of-Contents\/Display-your-first-snippet"]],"reference":"doc:\/\/tws-ios.TWS\/tutorials\/Tutorial-Table-of-Contents"},"metadata":{"categoryPathComponent":"Tutorial-Table-of-Contents","role":"project","category":"Learn to use the SDK","title":"Creating and managing TWSManager"},"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"patch":0,"minor":3},"references":{"doc://tws-ios.TWS/tutorials/TWS/CustomizingViews#Custom-loading-and-error-views":{"url":"\/tutorials\/tws\/customizingviews#Custom-loading-and-error-views","kind":"section","title":"Custom loading and error views","role":"pseudoSymbol","type":"section","abstract":[{"te